on political Islam and jihadism sheds new light on these questions. Moving beyond journalistic accounts, Fawaz Gerges provides a clear and compelling explanation of the deeper conditions that fuel ISIS. This new edition brings the story of ISIS to the present, covering key events—from the military defeat of its territorial state to the death of its leader al-Baghdadi—and analyzing how the ongoing Syrian, Iraqi, and Saudi-Iranian conflict could lead to ISIS’s revival.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aIslamic fundamentalism. 0aJihad. 0aTerrorismxReligious aspectsxIslam. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / World / Middle Eastern.2bisacsh  a2003 invasion of Iraq.  aAbu Anas al-Shami.  aAbu Ayyub al-Masri.  aAbu Bakr al-Baghdadi.  aAbu Fatima al-Jaheishi.  aAbu Ghraib prison.  aAbu Musab al-Zarqawi.  aAbu Muslim al-Turkmani.  aAbu Omar al-Baghdadi.  aAbu Qatada.  aAbu Yahya al-Libi.  aActivism.  aAdnan al-Aroor.  aAhrar al-Sham.  aAl-Nusra Front.  aAl-Qaeda in the Islamic Maghreb.  aAl-Qaeda.  aAl-Tawhid Brigade.  aAmerican-led intervention in Syria.  aAnsar al-Islam.  aAnti-Americanism.  aAnti-Shi'ism.  aAnwar al-Awlaki.  aApostasy.  aArab Spring.  aArmed Islamic Group of Algeria.  aAssociation of Muslim Scholars.  aBa'ath Party.  aBa'athism.  aBlitzkrieg.  aCaliphate.  aCataclysm (Dragonlance).  aCombatant.  aCounter-insurgency.  aDe-Ba'athification.  aEnglish Defence League.  aFaith campaign.  aFall of Mosul.  aFree Syrian Army.  aGeneral Military Council for Iraqi Revolutionaries.  aGod.  aGulf War.  aHaji Bakr.  aHaytham Manna.  aIdeology.  aInsurgency.  aIranian Revolution.  aIraq War.  aIraqis.  aIslam.  aIslamic Front for the Iraqi Resistance.  aIslamic State of Iraq and the Levant.  aIslamic State of Iraq.  aIslamic